The Public Protector said the mandate of the bank's monetary policy should change and that it should no longer focus on protecting the value of the currency. JOHANNESBURG - The rand has weakend by at least 1% after confirmation on Tuesday afternoon that the Reserve Bank has submitted its legal papers to have the public protector's remedial action regarding its mandate set aside.Earlier Eyewitness News reported that the Reserve Bank has submitted its application to the High Court to have the Public Protector's remedial action regarding its mandate set aside.Last week Advocate Busiswe Mkhwebane said that the bank had failed in its duties to protect the public by not ensuring that Absa bank repaid an apartheid-era bailout given to failed bank Bankorp.She also said the mandate of the bank's monetary policy should change and that it should no longer focus on protecting the value of the currency.Mkhwebane says the bank's mandate should be amended to one that promotes balanced and sustainable economic growth.He report also found that Absa should repay more than R1 billion it received from the bank as a bail-out to Bankorp during apartheid.The Constitutional Court has ruled that the public protector's findings are binding, but they can be challenged in court.The African National Congress's Secretary General, Gwede Mantashe last week weighed in on the matter, deeming Mkhwebane's decision overreach by the public protector.The recommendation has been widely criticised as over-reach by the Chapter 9 institution.(Edited by Zinhle Nkosi)